column5:
Fixed issue with DataLocationProxy#getLocation() returning null

Changed DataLocationProxy to work like HashChangeProxy so that it
returns an empty string rather than null when the current location
has not been set.  This fixes the issue that causes the app below to
fail with a 'path is null' error.

var app = $.sammy('div.app',function(a){
  a.setLocationProxy(new Sammy.DataLocationProxy(this));
  a.get('#/',function(){
    this.swap('Hello world')
  })
});
app.run('#/');

Allow plugins to be loaded by 'strings' to allow for better error messaging:

Like:

  use('Storage');

New: the contents of a regexp route match are now forwarded to the route callback as args.

For example:

  this.get(/\#\/route(\d+)/, function(context, num) {
    // runRoute #/route2
    // num == 2
  });

Changed the Sammy.Store KVO to send an object instead of multiple arguments [Thanks dpree!]

This makes Sammy.Store better conform with Sammy.Application#bind and #trigger
The object sent looks like {key: key, value:value}

Sammy around filters.

var app = $.sammy(function() {

  this.around(function(route) {
    if (this.isLoggedIn()) {
      route();
    } else {
      this.redirect('#', 'login');
    }
  })

});

routing with the callback as a string will lookup the method with the name and use it as the callback.

e.g.
  this.mygenericcallback = function () {};

  this.get('#/', 'mygenericcallback');

Dont require an app_function to be passed to the Sammy.Application constructor.

This allows a more object like approach to building apps. e.g.

  var new_app = $.sammy();

  new_app.get('#/', function() {
    // route logic here
  });

EventContext#redirect now makes use of Object#join so that you can redirect to a list of arguments

Example:
var three = '3';
this.redirect('#', 'one', 'two', three);

Sammy.Application#use() takes an app function and applys it to the current app.

This allows for a plugin/middleware structure based on reuseable app functions. For example, you could create a new templating plugin by defining a function like:

var MyTemplatingPlugin = function(a) {

  a.helpers({
    mytemplate: function(string) {
      return "<awesome>" + string + "</awesome>";
    }
  });

};

You could then 'use' it in your app (or multiple apps):

$.sammy(function() {

  use(MyTemplatingPlugin);

  get('#/', function() {
    this.mytemplate("I'm wrapped in awesome");
  });

});

The app function and route callbacks both yield _this_ as the first argument.

This means that have a quick shortcut to app and context, respectively, so you can stop using with(this) {} as much.

Example:

  $.sammy(function(a) {
    // a == this;
    a.get('#/', function(e) {
      // e == this;
      e.redirect('#/redirect');
    });
  })

Support for query strings in the URL fragment.

Adds support for key-value parameters in a query string that appears
after the hash.  The query string is ignored when looking up routes; so
you can pass arbitrary parameters to a Sammy action without changing the
route.

Query string parameters are mapped to the `params` object just
like path parameters and form values.  For example, this link:

    <a href="#/docs?page=3&per_page=15">next page of results</a>

Will route to this Sammy action:

    app = $.sammy(function() {
        this.get('#/docs', function() {
            show_results_page(this.params.page, this.params.per_page);
        });
    });

The syntax for query strings in the URL fragment is the same for
traditional query strings: the query is separated from the path by a
question mark; parameters are separated by ampersands; keys and values
are separated by equals signs.

Fixed: All forms were being bound but could never submit because _checkFormSubmission always returned false;

I rearranged the way 404's are thrown so that runRoute always raises 404s.
If silence_404 is on you will never see them unless you call runRoute() directly.
Instead _checkURL and _checkFormSubmission catch the 404 and decide what to do.
This is actually a good improvement as it means you never have to return from post() routes,
but if you want to you could do

  post('#/post-form', function() { with(this) {
    // do something to the form
    if (something) { // if something goes wrong or isnt correct
      return true; // will actually submit the form to the server
    }
  }});
